result.execSummary:
The defendant Kayla M Gutsch was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Harboring/Aiding a Felon-Falsify Info, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.47(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: - Pay the DNA surcharge, costs and disbursements.  Court ordered monies taken by the Department of Correction from up to 25% of prison funds.  Balance would be then be paid while on Extended Supervision.  Failure to pay amounts in full would result in a civil judgment entered against defendant.
with credit for THREE (3) days time served.

superMiscConds.notes: - 60-days from release, the Defendant has to find a job.
- No association with any gang members.
- Court advised that the defendant will have to provide a DNA sample to the Wisconsin State Crime Laboratory for DNA testing .

supervisions.notes:
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess any gun or other firearms. 
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
